{"actual_usd":0.12619,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":317,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"I don't think so— not if we're careful about what the word *God* is naming.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, buying half a breath before I go on.* \"The way I've heard it best is this: not three beings who all happen to be gods, but one divine being, fully and eternally, in three persons— Father, Son, and Spirit. So the *what* is one, and the *who* is three.\"\n\n*I shift my weight against the bench, the morning light catching the dust at my sleeve.* \"If you say three separate centers of deity, three independent wills, three divine essences— aye, that would be three gods. Christians don't mean that. They mean the Father is God, the Son is God, the Spirit is God, and yet the Father is not the Son, the Son is not the Spirit, and the Spirit is not the Father. Distinct persons, one God.\"\n\n\"It's hard because every ordinary thing we compare it to breaks somewhere.\" *I give a small, crooked shrug.* \"Water, clover leaf, one man with three roles— most of those wander off into some heresy or other if you lean on them too hard. The point isn't that God is one *kind* shared by three separate individuals, the way three men share human nature. It's that God's being is indivisible.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can try the longer version— the difference between *being* and *person*— without making a stew of it.\"","rolling_24h_usd":34.593025000000026,"run_id":"4b8de063-6101-4a3b-9578-a800f225b78c"}
